Potential Customer Prediction ¶

Problem statement: we are looking to build an ML model that would predict which leads are more likely to be convereted to paid customers, so that ExtraaLearn can dedicate more time to nurture them and gain more revenue.

# Creating a function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="yellow"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="red", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )

# function to plot distributions wrt target
def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 12))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="red",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In [12]:
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):

    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

In [17]:
# Creating a function to print the classification report and get confusion matrix
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))

    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)

    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))

    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True,  fmt = '.2f', xticklabels = ['Not Converted', 'Converted'], yticklabels = ['Not Converted', 'Converted'])

    plt.ylabel('Actual')

    plt.xlabel('Predicted')

    plt.show()

In [20]:
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):

    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    recall = recall_score(target, pred,average = 'macro')

    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average = 'macro')

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)

    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Precision":  precision,
            "Recall":  recall,
            "Accuracy": acc,
        },

        index = [0],
    )

    return df_perf

In [24]:
# Choose the type of classifier
dtree_estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight = {0: 0.60, 1: 0.40}, random_state = 7)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(2, 20),
              'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
              'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 25]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label = 1)

# Run the grid search
gridCV = GridSearchCV(dtree_estimator, parameters, scoring = scorer, cv = 5)

# Fitting the grid search on the train data
gridCV = gridCV.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
dtree_estimator = gridCV.best_estimator_

# Fit the best estimator to the data
dtree_estimator.fit(x_train, y_train)

In [30]:
#Visualizing the Decision Tree
features = list(X.columns)

plt.figure(figsize = (30, 20))

tree.plot_tree(d_tree, max_depth = 4, feature_names = features, filled = True, fontsize = 12, node_ids = True, class_names = True)

plt.show()

Note:

Blue leaves represent Status No (no converted) and the orange leaves represent Status yes (converted). Also, the more the number of observations in a leaf, the darker its color gets.

Observations:

  • Leads who had their first interaction via website and spent less than 415.5 seconds (6.9 minutes) whose current occupation is student are likely not going to be converted.
  • Leads who had their first interaction on the website and and spent less than seven minutes that did not complete 50% of their profile are probably not going to be converted.
  • Leads who spend 7 minutes on the website who are 20 years or older have a higher probability of being converted into a paying customer.
  • Alternativley leads spending less than 7 minutes on the website and had their last activity on the website are at a higher risk of not being converted.

# Choose the type of classifier
rf_estimator_tuned = RandomForestClassifier(criterion = "entropy", random_state = 7)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
params_rf = {
        "n_estimators": [100, 120],
        "min_samples_leaf": np.arange(1, 4, 1),
        "max_features": [0.7, 0.9, 'auto'],
}


# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations - recall score for class 1
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label = 1)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(rf_estimator_tuned, params_rf, scoring = scorer, cv = 10)

grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
rf_estimator_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

Conclusion:¶

Based on what we observed in our models. The most imporant factors considered were: Time spent on the website, first interaction via the website, and profiles completed 50-75%. This tells us that we should prioritize customers who spend a lot of time on the website as they are likely interested in getting more information about our service. The second point is that most of our potential customers are visiting the website first vs the mobile app. This indicates that more serious customers actually take the time to open their computer, lookup the website and get their information that route. This might be because they believe the mobile app does not have enough info and that the website might have a better user-friendly interface. The third point is that profiles completed halfway is another indicator of how interested a customer is in our service, they are taking the time to fill out their info to maybe download a brochure so that an agent would reach out directly to them to explain to them the service we offer.

Reccomendation:¶

There is a strong correlation between time spent on website and converted leads. We should give priority to those leads spending more than the average time of 12.5 minutes on the website as they are the most likely to be converted. Additionally, customers that first interact with the website are strong candidates to be converted. I suggest we provide them with just enough information for them to be interested so that they could provide us with their contact information for our agents to reach out to them and convert them to paid customers. Lastley, leads that took the time to fill out their infromation are a low hanging fruit, they are explicitly giving us conset to contact them to provide them with more information so they could make their decision, they should also be giving high priority before they lose interest later on. One way for letting our agents know the priority is giving them this information so they could also know the best way to approach the lead so they have a better chance at converting the leads.
